{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_sparks_ver01/data/sn85058379/00279554322/1908010401/0007.xml":{"full_text":"The Goldfield News\n\u201cAll That\u2019s New and True of the Greatest Gold Camp Ever Known\u201d\nVol. 4. No. 37. Goldfield, Esmeralda County, Nevada, Saturday, January 4, 1008,\nPROVED\nBEFORE\nPRINTED\ni- W\nREAD BY\nTHOUSANDS\nWEEKLY\nPrice 10 Cents\nPRODUCTION OF GOLDFIELD\nWARRANTS A BRANCH MINT\nNevada produced ore In 1907 of an approximate gross value of $26,\n000,000 and Goldfield-* share of It a as about one-half. Nevada la the only\nstate which assesses a bullion tax, which Is $4.70 on $100 of net production,\n75 cents going to the state treasury and the balance Into the county ex\nchequer. The bullion tax paid by Goldfield mines In the first nine months\nof 1907, according to sworn statements, was $197,830.33. On account of the\nchang' room dispute which closed the properties of the Goldfield Consoli\ndated, he year's third quarter was one of Its leanest; yet by affidavits filed\nwith the collector the gross product of Consolidated mines and leases In\nthat period was worth $1,683,104.14. that of the Florence $713,629.23 and\nthat of Jumbo Kxtenslon $383,105.18. The total gross output of these\nproperties was for the third quarter $2,679,838.65, the net was $1,440,093.79\nand the bullion tax $60,483.94.\nSuch a showing Is not overlooked by those who seek the establishment\nat Goldfield of a branch mint. The Carson mint Is literally flooded with\nGoHfleld gold. In November It shipped to this point $125,000 in coin and\na greater sum In December. In the final month of 1907 the Carson mint\nobliged to Install another strong box to care for the surplus yellow\ntreasure and It Is virtually assured that this plant will be reopened now\nfor coinage after having been closed for such purposes for over twelve\nyears.\ninvestigating route for\nA NEW RAILROAD TO ELY\nFrank C Armstrong, representing the\nallied Inteieats of the Cumberland Ely,\nNevada Con., Ely Mines. Steptoe Smelt\ning and Nevada Northern Railway com\npanies, accompanied by Arthur Scott, a\nciril engineer, left this morning in \"Tex\"\nRickard's automobile \u2018or Tooopah and\nColdfield.\nThe Prim >ry object of Mr Arm-I\nstrong's visit to the southern ramps at\nthis time, and In taking the overland\ntrip, Is to investigate the topography of\nthe Intervenin country to determine i\nthe feasibility of the proposed railroad j\nfrom Ely to the aouthern camps, and, j\nIncidentally, to make a thorough can- t\nvass of the mines In that section, to as\ncertain the amount of ore available at\npresent and the future possibilities of\nthe section in the way of shipments to\nthe smelter here.\nSome fourteen months ago. two pre- j\nliminary surveys were made from To-\nnopah to this camp, by engineers In the\nemploy of the Tonopah people, presum\nably the Tonopah-E',y Railway com\npany. Beginning at Tonopah these sur\nveyors followed the low passes In the\nmountain ranges and the valleys Into\nEly.\nOne route, leaving the White Rlvpr\nvalley thirty-five miles south of Ely,\ncrossed the Schell creek range, through\nWater canyon, entering Steptoe valley\nsouth of Ward, thence northward down\nSteptoe valley Into Ely, by way of\nGeorgetown. The other route came up\nWhite River valley to Its head and the\nsummit of the range, thence down Mur\nray creek canyon into Ely. From the\nsummit of the range at this point a line\nwas also run around by the Giroux mine,\nand down Robinson canyon into Ely.\nWhile he refused to give out anything\nfor publication concerning the nature of\nhis visit to the southern camps and the\ncountry through which he proposes to\ngo. It Is generally understood that in\nleaving this city. Mr. Armstrong has\nchosen an altogether different route\nthan any heretofore proposed. Having\nIn mind the possible extension of the\nNevada Northern, he went out by way\nof Hamilton, Duckwater and Tybo, to\ngain Information as to the feasibility of\nconstructing a railroad through that\nsection and to take observations of the\npossibilities of the country in general.\nEarly last fall it was generally under\nstood, both here and In Tonopah, that\nwork on the Tonopah-Ely railroad would\nbe actually begun before the first of the\nyear; that sufficient money to Insure its\nconstruction and completion had al\nready been raised by the promoters, but\nwhen the financial panic took possession\nof the country In general, this, like\nmany other new enterprises, was forced\nto await more favorable times.\u2014Ely Ex\npositor.\nKANT CLAIMS LOCATED\nriMT OP THE TEAS\nThe usual midnight rush to locate\nclaims on which the required annual as\nsessment work for 1907 was not done,\n\u2018cfc In-*. Tow-day -dfrht. The\nweather was Ideal, a tremendous con\ntrast to the two years previous, when\nstrong blizzards were raging, and there\nwas a small army of men in the hills\nlong before midnight. There were more\nclaims or en this year than ordinarily. I\nmany hoping the Bartlett bill, remitting\nthe work, would go through, and others 1\nbeing unable to raise the money to do\nthe work owing to the financial up\nheavel. Many outsiders wired In in\nstructions to start work on the last day\nof the year, but that there were plenty\nvith work unperformed is vouched for\nby everyone who went out, one man\nhaving located twelve claims. Most of\nthe property was on the outskirts of the\ncamp, and undoubtedly many claims\nwere filed on by mistake.\nRECEIVES APPOINTED\nPOB BONNIE CLARE\nG. R. Yearsley has been appointed re\nceiver for the Bonnie Clare Mining and\nMilling company of Nye and Ksmeralda\ncounties. The 10-stamp mill, which has\nbeen doing excellent work for the past\nseveral weeks, has been temporarily\nclosed down. The company had been\nemploying Sa men at the mines and the\nmill.\nCLAUSE C. I1TMAN BE HUES\nFROM EIBE DEPIITH 3TT\nClaude C. Inman, who has been \u2019r,ef\nof the fire department since Its organ\nization four years ago, has tendered his\nresignation to the eonntr commissioners,\nhaving other c.-fal.-.-** tha# require so\nmuch attention that he is unable to de\nvote the time necessary to the position.\nHe believes the new chief should give\nhis entire time to the department and\nreceive a salary In keeping with the\nposition.\nMr. Inman has built up the depart\nment to a high position of efficiency,\nand has kept the fire losses down to u\nlow figure while working under more\nthan the ordinary disadvantages inci\ndent to a new mining camp.\nKXOHQBADEBS ESCAPE FBOM JAIL\nThat highgraders are slippery custom\ners is attested by the escape of two of\nthem from the county jail this week,\nwhile three more have Jumped their\nbonds. John Riley and D. O\u2019Donnell,\nwho escaped from jail, were caught com\ning out of the Rogers-Syndicate lease\non the Florence, with ore in their pos\nsession. They were unable to obtain\nbonds and were committed to Jail pend\ning trial. They made their get-away\nearly Wednesday morning while taking\nexercise in the jail yard, the jailer hav\ning stepped into the telephone room for\na moment. Deputy sheriffs and detec\ntives have made an extensive search for\nthem, but without results so far.\nI MAY SOON HAVE ANOTHER\nJUDGE IN THIS DISTRICT\nIn contemplation of the cajl for the\nspecial session of the legislature the\nChamber of Commerce wired Governor\nSparks asking; him to Include in the\ncall measures for the relief of the con\nrestlon of litigation in the district court\nn this county. The ueaiage follows:\n\u201cCitizens of Esmeralda county earn\nstly request you to include In call for\nixtra session, matter of increase of\nlumber of judges for first judicial dis\nrlct. Four hundred cnses now on file\nn clerk's office for Esmeralda county\ndone. Jail full to overflowing of per\n10ns accused of crimes awaiting trial,\ndorc business than one Judge could at\nend to If sitting continuously in this\nfounty alone. Court facilities In this\nlistrict same as before Goldfield ex\nsted. Practically impossible to have\nases heard. Present Judge now en\n;aged In business of four other counties\nif the district, and will be so engaged\nitxty to ninety days longer. Legislative\nellef urgrently needed.\n\u25a0GOLDFIELD CHAMBER OF COM\nMERCE.\n\u201cC. S. SPRAGUE, Chairman.\u201d\nThe message was sent last Sunday\nnight and Monday Mr. Sprague reeelved\nreply from Governor Sparks advising\nthat he had had the matter under con\nsideration for some time and was glad\nthat he had an early opportunity to af\nford tho necessary relief.\nEsmeralda county is in the first judi\ncial district, which includes four other\ncounties, while the amount of litigation\nin this county alone would keep several\nJudges busy for months. When'Judge\nLangan left here the latter part of No\nvember he stated that it would probably\nbe March or April before he would be\nable to return, his duties in the other\ncounties requiring several months time.\nThe appointment of an additional judge\nfor this district would afford some re\nlief to the present crowded condition of\nthe docket. As it is now it would take\nover a year to get action on a civil case\nin the court, as the preferenceMs given\nto criminal cases as being more urgent.\n^EW CHLORINATION MILL\nIS .NEARING COMPLETION\nDtl\nThe ptafK ,f tJte^Qoldfle'd Chlorlna\nT \u20191 fomrrwiv Vear Columbia. Is\npidly n.arl'g W.Aletlon. and It Is\nped to b lr, sh<H\u00bb. to handle ore early\nmonth life. has i>een conslder\ndelu- It-ulnrt, the machinery\n-*rom 1 !'va but anr'hcr thirty\nwin ptoii.ib\u00ae bo anWeient to get\nrythlng in rurjjing ord^r\nhe mill will tW, a daily capacity\ntons, and as its name indicates, wt\u20197\nfrom the ores by the\nsb. supplemented by\ntment The method\ne new features, anc\nted on QoMfleld ores\non of the plant was\nset the 4\nrl nation j r^|\nHectrolytic\ntontal';5\nthorough1 v j\nt* construe\nstarted. Both ores and concentrates\nwere used In the test*, the saving ef\nfected on ores being 95 per c#nt, and\non concentrates, 98 per cent. Both oxide\nand sulphide ores were used In the tests,\nwhich were successful In every instance.\nWith the plant In operation the comp\nany will he In the market as ore pur\nchasers, and will afford an outlet for\nvr\u00abt quantities .,f low anl medium grade\nores, not only of this rttstrcit, but also\ntt on nearby camps. Gold Mountnln and\nStjmler both have tremendous bodies of\nmilling grade ore that would leave\nsmall profit to the producers If shipped\nts smelters, but which can be profitably\ni ated In Goldfield on account of the\n.ort haul.\nBACKBONE OF THE STRIKE\nIN GOLDFIELD IS BROKEN\nSeveral Properties Resumed Operations Today with\nIndependent Workers and Former Members\nof the Western Federation Who Have\nRenounced Their Allegiance\nThe backbone of the strike in Goldfield is about broken, and from this time on, it will be all one way.\nMembers of the Western Federation of Miners are breaking away in numbers and mines are gradually re\nsuming.\nThis (Saturday) morning, the Combination Fraction, after an idleness of five weeks, resumed with three\nshifts, many of the men being former Western Federation men who had seceded from the organisation.\nThe Mohawk proper also resumed work this morning with former members of the Federation and with im\nportations from California and Utah.\nThe two Becker leases on the Atlanta also resumed, with entirely new men brought into camp by the\nmanager. They are among the best miners on the coast.\nThe von Polenz lease on the Florence was among those to start up, working a full complement of men,\nmany of the miners being former Western Federation men.\nWAGE SCALE AND CARD SYSTEM REMAIN\nThe men are going to work under the card system and under the new scale of wages adopted by the mine\nowners.\n\u201cYOU CAN SAY THAT NOT A SINGLE MAN WHO BELONGS TO THE WESTERN FEDERATION\nOF MINERS CAN GO TO WORK UPON ANY OF THE PROPERTIES OF THE ASSOCIATION, WITHOUT\nFIRST RENOUNCING HIS ALLEGIANCE TO THAT ORGANIZATION,\u201d SAID GENERAL MANAGER\nMACKENZIE THIS MORNING. \u201cAND YOU MAY ALSO SAY THAT THE ASSOCIATION IS ADHERING\nTO ITS NEW WAGE SCALE AND WILL ADHERE TO IT, WHATEI'ER MAY BE THE REPORTS OR BE\nLIEF TO THE CONTRARY. THE CARD SYSTEM AND THE WAGE SCALE STAND WITHOUT AN IOTA\nOF CHANCE. THE LEASERS OF THE CAMP ARE ALL PAYING THE NEW SCALE, AS FOR THE\nCONSOLIDATED NO ONE CAN LEASE ON OUR PROPERTY WHO PAYS MORE THAN THE NEW\nSCALE.\"\nGOLDFIELD AN OPEN CAMP\nGoldfield is to be an open camp, that is, open to all union labor except members of the Western Federation\nof Miners. Absolutely no Western Federation men will be employed while bolding allegiance to that union.\nA movement is upon foot by many Western Feders ton men to form a new union entirely separate from\nthe Federation, based upon the old Virginia City Union, .nd embracing the whole state. The movement has\nmade considerable progress and there is reason to believe that the rank and file will desert the Western Federa\ntion the moment the new membership roll is open for signatures. The miners are becoming convinced that the\nMine Operators\u2019 Association intends to remain firm and fight it out if it takes a year. So they are beginning to\nconsider any new plan whereby they can go to work as union men and still meet the demands of the operators.\nCALL FOR AN EXTRA SESSION\nGovernor Sparks has issued a call convening the legislature in extraordinary session. He has not made\nknown in full the purposes of the call, but it is understood that it has to do with the enactment of legislation to\nmore thoroughly police the state. It is believed that he will also recommend the creating of a new judgeship for\nEsmeralda county, as under the present system, the courts cannot possibly take care of the business demanding\nattention.\nOn Friday morning part of the troops were ordered back to their various stations in California. Some 160\nmen were left, the pick of the well-seasoned and experienced campaigners. There has been no intimation given\nas to how long these troops will remain, but at least until after the adjournment of the legislature and the polic\ning of the state under any new laws that might be passed.\n\nDAILY MILLING CAPACITY OF 4,000 TONS\nIN EIGHT OF NEVADA\u2019S CAMPS IN 1908\nMilling of Nevada\u2019s comparatively low-grade grist is\nto prove one of the most important considerations of 1908.\nThe fo\u201d Mug number of stamps may be depended upon to\nbe droj g daily in these eight camps before the coming\nof anoti- winter\u2019s snows:\nColdfield\nTonopch\nBallfr _\nHilver !''ak\nManhattan\nBerlin\nBonnie Claire\nBound Mountain\n230\n220\n200\n120\n30\n20\n20\n10\nThat is a -total of 850 stamps, with a daily grind on\n4,250 tons, worth at only an average of $25 the ton, $106,\n250 a day or $38,781,250 per annum.\nThe smelting conditions are to be infinitely more satis\nfactory throughout this year than during the last months\nof 1907. All in a heap came the financial panic, an increase\nof smelter rates caused by excess charges in transportation\nand the refusal of the reduction plants to make settlement\non ore received within sixty days after delivery. The\nGoldfield chamber of commerce took the initiative in a\nstate-wide movement looking to relief. On the night of\nDecember 4 Nevada mining men representing wealth to\nthe amount of $70,000,000 secretly met in Reno and dis\ncussed plans for the erection of a mammoth smelter and\ncustom mill at some convenient point in the state. Now\nthe American Smelting and Refining company agrees to\npay cash for low-grade ores and part cash for high-grade,\nwhile the Golden Cycle works at Colorado Springs, whose\ncapacity is 900 tons a day, offers vo settle in spot cash on\ncontrols. The American trust is considering a sweeping\nreduction in smelter rates.\nYEAR\u2019S PRODUCTION, $11,766,800\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nIn the year of 1907 Goldfield mines and ?ases shipped 117,668 tons of ore, worth, at an estimated average\nvalue of $100 per ton, $11,766,800. The weekly average production was 2263 tons of ore, valued at $226,300.\nLabor troubles made absolute production blanks of eight of the year\u2019s fifty-two weeks, enforcing an idle\nness that foots up to 15.37 per cent, not counting loss of addition time caused by flooding of the diggings and\nother hindrances. The actual production of $11,766,800, therefore, is only 81.63 per cent of what the year should\nhave accomplished under normal industrial conditions. Allowed to operate in peace, according to these figures,\nGoldfield properties would have swollen the world\u2019s wealth by $13,903,814 in the past year.\nThe banner tonnage week was that one ended October 26. Its production was 71900 tons, which is 218\nper cent above the weekly average and sets a pace that means $37,388,000 per annum. It is not extravagant to\nstate that such a mark is among the possibilities of 1903.\nThe following table gives the tonnage and values for each week of the year:\nWeek ending January 5 3,111 tons\nWeek ending January 12.-. 1,789 tons\nWeek ending January 19 1,920 tons\nWeek ending January 26 1,620 tons\nWeek ending February 2 1,289 tons\nWeek ending February 9 1,112 tons\nWeek ending February 16 1,016 tons\nWeek ending February 23 1,572 tons\nWeek ending March 2 1,338 tons\nWeek ending March 9 518 tons\nWeek ending March 16. I\u00ae7 tons\nWeek ending March 23\nWeek ending March 30\nWeek ending April 6\nWeek ending April 13\nWeek ending April 20\nWeek ending April 27 512 tons\nWeek ending May 4 952 t\u00b0ns\nWeek ending May-11 873 tons\nWeek ending May 18 1,016 tons\nWeek ending May 25 *.|52 tons\nWeek ending June 1 \u2018ons\nWeek ending June 8 1.824 tons\nWeek ending June 15 1.519 *ons\nWeek ending June 22 2,991 tons\nWeek ending June 29 3,588 tons\nWeek ending July 6\nWeek ending July 13\nWeek ending July 20\nWeek ending July 27\nWeek ending August 3\nWeek ending August 10\nWeek ending August 17\nWeek ending August 24\nWeek ending August 31\nWeek ending September 7\nWeek ending September 14\nWeek ending September 21\nWeek ending September 28\nWeek ending October 5\nWeek ending October 12\nWeek ending October 19\nWeek ending October 26\nWeek ending November 2\nWeek ending November 9\nWe-sk ending November 16\nV, r aiding November 23\nWei* ending November 30\nWeek ending December 7\nWeek ending December 14\nWeek ending December 21\nWee*- ending December 28\n3,384 tons\n3,919 tons\n4,015 tons\n3,369 tons\n4,044 tons\n4,074 tons\n3,814 tons\n3,559 tons\n2,233 tons\n1,730 tons\n2,425 tons\n3,494 tons\n3,744 tons\n3,764 tons\n3,877 tons\n5,406 tons\n7,190 tons\n3,741 tons\n1,945 tons\n4,830 tons\n5,784 tons\n3,777 tons\n1,810 tons\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nestimated\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\nvalue\n$311,100\n178.900\n192.000\n162.000\n128.900\n111,200\n101,600\n157,200\n133,800\n51,800\n46,700\n51.200\n96.200\n87,300\n101,600\n143,200\n144.100\n162.400\n154.900\n299.100\n358,800\n338.400\n391.900\n401.500\n336.900\n404.400\n407.400\n381.400\n355.900\n223,300\n173.000\n242.500\n349.400\n374.400\n376.400\n387.700\n540,600\n719.000\n374.100\n194.500\n483.000\n578.400\n377.700\n181.000\nTotals\n117.668 tons: estimated value\n$11,766,800\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nNEVADA GETS THIRD PLACE\nIN GOLD PRODUCING STATES\nThe preliminary report of the director of the mint, Just leaned, ihowi\nNevada to he third In the Hat of gold producing elates for the year 1907.\nColorado leads In the production of gold, and Montana In the production of\nsilver. Alaska produced almost ns much gold in 1907 as Colorado, but\nahoUrs a falling ofr from 1906 of over 93.000,000. Colorado also produced\nabout $2,000,000 less than In 1900, while Nevada shows an increase. Ne\nvada has made great strides in the past three yeara nnd at the present\nrate of increase !n gold production It will soon be at the head of the gold\nproducing states. The greater part of this Increase can be credited to Gold\nfield. but with the many mills that are now either In process of construc\ntion, or recently put In operation. In the various other camps of the state\n\u2014which will soon be adding their quota to the output of the yellow metal\n\u2014It would only be necessary to have one year of steady work In this\nstnte to make It the leader. The production of gold and silver is shown\nIn the following table:\nAlaska\nColorado\nCalifornia\nNevada\nMontana\nI\u2019tah\nIdaho\nGold\n$i8.25i.6io\n20.888.833\n17,394,862\n14,701,658\n4,206.345\n4.652.941\n1.087,655\nSilver\nt 98,081\n7,687,769\n1,535.281\n5,126,556\n7,997,880\n7,757.390\n4,605.293\nNEW YEAR WILL WITNESS\nMORE ACTIVITY AT WONDER\nWonder, Nov., Jan. 1.\u2014With the ad\nvent of the new year work will oom\nmenoe In the mine* here with renewed\nvigor. Tills Is assured by the fact that\nthe minors of the district will ho re\nlieved by that time of the necessity of\nlooking after ,annual assessment work\nfor outsiders. It Is estimated that the\nannual work required cost no loss than\n$50,000 In the district. Rome even place\nthe figures higher, taking into account\nas they do the stretch of country lying\nbetween the Fairvlew district and Won\nder.\nBcarcely a foot of this territory, 17\nmiles in length, between the rival camps\nla open to location. The hillsides look\nas though a lot of prehistoric gophers\nhad been grubbing In them. At any\ntime a new town may spring Into exist\nence near the spot where the deepest\nholes have been dug. It Is only with\ndepth that the human gophers find the\nreal kernel In the mineral nut. That the\ntown will be located not many miles dis\ntant from the Wonder cltunner ground\nIs the conclusion of virtually every\nvisitor to the district.\nA. V. Ronald. the Fairvlew banker. Is\nheavily Interested In this enterprise and\nIs sending the tunnel into the hill to cut j\nthe ledge at a rapid rate. Three dig-\ntlnct ledges have been opened up on this\nground and assays running as high as\n$000 to the ton In gold and silver have\nbeen secured. Another man Interested\nin adjacent property is John K. Pelton\nof Wonder. Mr. Pelton has an option on\nI seven claims not far from Stunner j\nground that give the best surface show\nI ings ever secured in the Wonder district\noutside of the Jack Pot, Ruby Wonder\narid Nevada Wonder. The ore contains\na great deal of lead, which Is a decided\nadvantage when It comes to the smelter.\nApropos of smelters, C. M. bane, who\nwith Colonel Coyle has the Coyle-T-ane\ni lease on the group of claims owned by\nJudge Ross near the Yankee Doodle\nground, has become interested In an oil\nburning smelter which he predicts will\nsolve the problem of the Nevada mines.\nAccording to Mr. Dane who left Wonder\nfor Goldfield a few days rfgo, the r. jW\nsmelter has passed out of the experi\nmental stage. He asserts that even after\nthe exorbitant freight rates on crude oil\nhave been paid from Bakersfield to Reno,\nIt will still be possible to cut under the\ntrust charges for treating ore from $2\nto $4 a ton.\nThe object of his visit to Goldfield Is\nto secure the co-operation of the Gold\nfield mine owners. According to his\npresent plans he will erect one of the\noil burning smelters near Hazen, which\nhe thinks will be a central point in the\nmining industry of the state for a cen\ntury. That there Is some logic In his\nassertion, aside possibly from the time\nlimit, Is evident from the dtermination\nof the Western Ore Purchasing com\npany to erect its plant at the little cut\nthroat, hamlet where the Goldfield. Fal\nlon and train roads m\u00ab-et. Mr. Snyder,\nmanager of the purchasing company,\nstated recently that aside from his con\ntroversy with the railroads over the nn\njust rate on ore en transit, while the\nplant was at Reno, the fact that Wonder,\nFalrvlew and now Rawhide would be\ndirectly tributary to Haxen decided him\nto build his plant at that place.\nMr. l-ane contends that the question\nof fluxes will not affect the oil burning\nsmelter in the least. He says that fully\n20 per cent more silica may be contained\nIn the ore than under the present meth\nods used by the trust in treatment of\nNevada ores, to secure relatively the\nsame results. The discovery of ore with\na large percentage of lead near Wonder\nwas especially gratifying to him. He\nrecently Invetlgated the silver-lead\nmines near Wlnnemucca and will make\nthem tributary to his plant, he avers, a*\nsoon as it 1# In running order. When he\nleft Wonder he was extremely confident\nof success, based largely on the fact,\nhe says, that a flve-ton oil burning\nsmelter had been Operated successfully;\nthat the Inventor of it plso Invented the\nmethod of smelting ore used by the\ntrust, and above all that the time is op\nportune for the building of such a plant\nthat will mean more to the advancement\nof Nevada as a mining state than -the\ndiscovery of twenty new districts, even\nif these are as good ns Wonder.\nThere was some excitement over at\nthe Ruby Wonder when it became evi\ndent that old mother nature was deter\nmined to take a hand In the distribution\nof Christmas presents. Xt seems that\nthe men employed on this estate begged\nSuperintendent Harris as a special favor\nto allow them to discontinue work In the\nshaft for a few days so that they might\nhave an opportunity to do some annual\nassessment work on a few claims owned\nby them in the district. Reluctantly\nMr. Harris granted the request. The\nnext day he went down the shaft and\nstruck a few blows with a hand pick\namong the rock that had been slightly\nloosened by the last shot set off by the\nminers before they quit. Very soon he\nrecognized the never falling sign of pay\nrock.\nThere was some talk of putting Won\nder on a $4 basis for miners. Percy\nFuller, general manager of the Battle\nship estate, contributed not a little to\n(he termination of further discussion of\nthe question. He argued that as long as\nhe had anything to do with the Battle\nship property, the iiiiiicrs should re\nceive not less than $5 per day. It de\nveloped later that the Spider-Wasp\nmanagement had also decided to con\ntinue the $5 scale when operations com\nmence after January 1. On the Jack\nPot and Ruby and the Christmas Won\nder the old scale of wages will alto be\nmaintained.\nSENATOR NEWLANDS FAVORS\nORGANIZING STATE POLICE\nSenator Newlands Is In favor of or\nganizing a state police force for use In\nNevada, and embodies his Ideas In the\nfollowing telegram which he sent to\nGovernor Sparks:\n'My opinion Is that In order to justify\nthe national government In using its\narmed forces to protect the state against\nviolence, it Is necessary, under the con\nstitution that application be made by\nthe legislature or, when the legislature\nconnot be convened, by the governor. It\nIs necessary, therefore, for you, in my\njudgment, to convene the legislature\nand obtain Its decision as to whether ap\nplication be made to the president for\nprotection, or art adequate law panned\nfor organizalng a state police force\nwhich will maintain order and protect\nlife and property. Individually, I be\nlieve In the latter course, and that the\ngood name of Nevada requires that it\nassert Itself to maintain order and pro\ntect life and property within 11s borders.\nThat duty Is a plain police force that\nshould not be under control or paid by\neither mine owner* w miner*, but should\nstand aloof from the Industrial contest\nbetween them, with a single eye to the\nmaintenance of order and to protect life\nand property.\n\u201c'In all you have done I recognise the\ndifficulty of the situation, your patriotic\nIntentions and your desire to prevent\nviolence and bloodsheli In the Interest of\ngood government: but it Is true that the\nstate must sooner or later assert Its\nsovereignty and Its firm determination\u2014\nunaided by the national government\u2014to\nsuppress all violence, and I believe the\ntime Is now. I can not believe the leg\nislature can fall to act promptly and de\ncisively. If It does not so act the re\nsponsibility Is theirs: not yours.\u201d\nnr ASA BAOX.S8\nTwo miles west of Goldfield, in a vir\ngin country, the Nevada Kagle, managed\nby John Houlihan, has a shaft down\n250 feet In mineral ground so promising\nas to have Justified the recent Installa\ntion of machine drills.\nLITTLE FLORENCE SHIPPING\nAT RATE OF $200,000 WEEKLY\nHigh grade ore from the 2,200-tons\ndump of the Little Florence lease Is be\ning loaded for consignment to the Am\nerican Smelting and Refining company's\nGolbe smelter at Denver, which pays\npart cash and the balance In sixty days.\nThe dump Is roughly valued at a half\nmillion dollars and It will require about\n56 cars to transport. Steady shipments\nwill go forward at the rate of about\n1200,000 a week and the lease, which\nhas 68 days to rut} from the date of un\nderground resumption of work, will add\nat least another million dollars to its\nprise record. No further sloping will\nbe undertaken until the management\nmay depend upon the retention of a full\ncrew of miners, since it will be the pol\nicy to make the greatest possible ton\nnage for every day remaining to the\nlease's life.\nScreening of the' waste dump of the\nMohawk-Flcrence, a Bub-lease on the\nLittle Ihorence, is rapidly progressing\nand from the pile there will be shipped\nseveral hundreds of tons of rich truck.\nOn company account the Florence will\nemploy the utmost force possible to ac\ncommodate in its extensive diggings\nand start mining on a broad scale aa\nsoon as it i big mill is ready to go into\ncommission, which will be but a few\nweeks herce. A plentiful supply of\nwater lias been secured by the pur\nchase of Indian springs, whose flow is\nnow 17.VOOO gallons dally and may be\neasily Increased to a much larger vol\nume. The fall from the springs the\nJHO.OOO- gallons reservoir is abou k\nfeet and the pipe line Is finished.","height":"29892","width":"21272"}}
